-- Seed learning track phases, items, and content blocks.
-- Generated by scripts/generate-seed-migration.ts from the live DB state.
-- Idempotent: re-run with SELECT public.seed_learning_track(); any time.

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION public.seed_learning_track()
RETURNS void
LANGUAGE plpgsql
SECURITY DEFINER
SET search_path = public
AS $seed$
DECLARE
  v_phase_id uuid;
  v_item_id  uuid;
BEGIN
  -- Clear existing (cascades through items -> content_blocks)
  DELETE FROM public.learning_track_phases;

  -- Phase: post_rnf / 1 / Foundation & Compliance

  -- Phase: post_rnf / 2 / Business Planning & Marketing Setup

  -- Phase: post_rnf / 3 / Sales Practice & Field Observation

  -- Phase: post_rnf / 4 / Learning & Team Contribution

  -- Phase: pre_rnf / 1 / Phase 1 — Foundation & Compliance

  -- Phase: pre_rnf / 2 / Phase 2 — Sales Skills & Presentations
1. Protection — insurance foundation
2. Savings — emergency fund (3-6 months)
3. Investment — wealth accumulation
4. Distribution — retirement & estate

Always address the bottom layers first before recommending wealth products.', NULL, NULL, NULL);
• Goal-driven ILP — ideal for clients with specific milestones (children''s education, retirement, wealth accumulation)
• Curated fund selection with top-up flexibility
• Policy loan feature for liquidity without surrendering
• Bonus allocation tiers reward higher premiums

**Handling the ''high fees'' objection:**
Explain dollar-cost averaging — regular premiums smooth out market volatility over time. Emphasise the value of curated fund access and professional fund management vs. DIY investing.

**Advisor tip:** Always use goal-based illustrations. Don''t sell the product — sell the outcome. "In 15 years, this could fund your child''s university education."', NULL, NULL, NULL);

  -- Phase: pre_rnf / 3 / Phase 3 — Prospecting & Market Outreach
• Hot market — family, close friends (highest trust, easiest to approach)
• Warm market — colleagues, acquaintances, ex-classmates
• Luke-warm market — friends of friends, social media connections

Start with hot, then work outward. The goal is 100 names before you make your first call.', NULL, NULL, NULL);
1. Open: "Hey [name], I''m doing a quick survey for my training — takes 2 min, mind helping?"
2. Questions: Current insurance coverage? Biggest financial concern? Saving for anything specific?
3. Close: "Thanks! Based on what you shared, I might have some insights — would you be open to a 15-min chat sometime?"', NULL, NULL, NULL);

  -- Phase: pre_rnf / 4 / Phase 4 — Field Work & Observations
1. How did the advisor build rapport in the first 5 minutes?
2. What questions did they ask? In what order?
3. How did they handle objections or resistance?
4. What body language did you notice (both advisor and client)?
5. How did they transition from fact-finding to presenting a solution?
6. How did they ask for the close?
7. What would YOU do differently?

Write your observations immediately after the meeting — don''t wait.', NULL, NULL, NULL);
1. Request existing policies from the person
2. List all current coverage: type, sum assured, premium, maturity date
3. Identify gaps against recommended coverage levels
4. Note any duplicate or over-insured areas
5. Present the summary with clear recommendations', NULL, NULL, NULL);

  -- Phase: pre_rnf / 5 / Phase 5 — Learning & Team Contributions
1. Why this article — what caught your attention, why it''s relevant
2. Key insights — 3-5 main takeaways (analyse, don''t just summarize)
3. How we can apply this — practical applications for the team
4. Discussion — pose 1-2 questions to spark team conversation', NULL, NULL, NULL);

END;
$seed$;

-- Apply the seed once at migration time
SELECT public.seed_learning_track();
